The leaders of Malaysia's ruling party met to discuss a replacement for ousted deputy prime minister Anwar Ibrahim, who faces trial next month in a case that will test the country's legal system.
The party leaders, who have been conducting a national campaign to explain to Malaysians why the popular Anwar was fired Sept. 2, will also confer on what to do now that the High Court judge has banned all comments on Anwar's guilt or innocence.
The arrest of former Malaysian Deputy Prime Minister Ibrahim won 't lead to massive social unrest or frighten away investors.
